                        body: '<p>Cato\'s political career is inseparable from his Stoic philosophy. For the Stoics, <em>virtus</em> (virtue, moral excellence) is the only true good. Wealth, power, reputation, even life itself are <em>indifferentia</em> \u2014 things indifferent, neither good nor bad in themselves. What matters is whether you act rightly.</p><p>This is not abstract philosophy for Cato. He applies it literally. If a law is unjust, he opposes it regardless of political consequences. If a compromise would require tolerating corruption, he refuses it. If defending the Republic means death, he accepts death. There is no calculation of advantage, no weighing of outcomes \u2014 only the question of whether an action is virtuous.</p>'
